Adding to science and technology has happened throughout the country's history. [[Cartography|cartographer]] [[Gerardus Mercator]], [[anatomy|anatomist]] [[Andreas Vesalius]], [[herbalist]] [[Rembert Dodoens]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Rembert Dodoens: iets over zijn leven en werk—Dodoens' werken|date=December 20, 2005|work=Plantaardigheden—Project Rembert Dodoens (Rembertus Dodonaeus)|language=Dutch|publisher=Stichting Kruidenhoeve/Plantaardigheden|location=Balkbrug|url=http://plantaardigheden.nl/dodoens/over_dodoens/leven_en_werk.htm#dodoens|accessdate=May 17, 2007|archive-date=June 10, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070610070835/http://www.plantaardigheden.nl/dodoens/over_dodoens/leven_en_werk.htm#dodoens|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Simon Stevin|author=O'Connor, J. J.; Robertson, E. F.|publisher=School of Mathematics and Statistics, University of St Andrews, Scotland|year=2004|url=http://www-groups.dcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Stevin.html|accessdate=May 11, 2007|archive-date=June 9, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070609192011/http://www-groups.dcs.st-andrews.ac.uk/~history/Biographies/Stevin.html|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Abstract (*)|journal=American Journal of Nephrology|year=1999|volume=19|issue=2|pages=282–289|publisher=S. Karger AG, Basel|doi=10.1159/000013462|url=http://content.karger.com/ProdukteDB/produkte.asp?Aktion=ShowPDF&ProduktNr=223979&Ausgabe=225203&ArtikelNr=13462|accessdate=May 11, 2007|last1=Broe|first1=Marc E. De|last2=De Weerdt|first2=D. L.|last3=Ysebaert|first3=D. K.|last4=Vercauteren|first4=S. R.|last5=De Greef|first5=K. E.|last6=De Broe|first6=L. C.|pmid=10213829|s2cid=2592970 | issn=0250-8095 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title='A Day Without Yesterday': Georges Lemaitre & the Big Bang|date=March 24, 2000|pages=18–19|author=Midbon, Mark, [[University of Wisconsin–Madison]]|publisher=[[Commonweal]], republished: Catholic Education Resource Center (<span style="font-size:87%;">CERC</span>)|url=http://www.catholiceducation.org/articles/science/sc0022.html|accessdate=June 7, 2007|archive-date=July 6, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070706021420/http://www.catholiceducation.org/articles/science/sc0022.html|url-status=dead}}</ref> and [[mathematics|mathematician]] [[Simon Stevin]] are among the most influential scientists.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Fair Face of Flanders|author=Patricia Carson|year=1969|page=136|isbn=90-209-4385-5|publisher=Lannoo Uitgeverij}}</ref>

Chemist [[Ernest Solvay]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Dictionary of the History of Technology|page=1135|author=Lance Day|editor=Lance Day, Ian McNeil|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|isbn=0-203-02829-5}}</ref> and engineer [[Zenobe Gramme]]<ref>{{cite book|title=Biographical Dictionary of the History of Technology|page=523|author=Gordon Woodward|editor=Lance Day, Ian McNeil|publisher=Routledge|year=2003|isbn=0-203-02829-5}}</ref> gave their names to the [[Solvay process]] and the [[Gramme dynamo]] in the 1860s. [[Bakelite]] was formed in 1907–1909 by [[Leo Baekeland]]. A major addition to science was also due to a Belgian, [[Georges Lemaître]]. He is the one who made the [[Big Bang]] theory of the start of the universe in 1927.<ref>{{cite web|title=Georges Lemaître, Father of the Big Bang|url=http://www.amnh.org/education/resources/rfl/web/essaybooks/cosmic/p_lemaitre.html|publisher=[[American Museum of Natural History]]|year=2000|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref>

Three [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine|Nobel Prizes in Physiology or Medicine]] were awarded to Belgians: [[Jules Bordet]] in 1919, [[Corneille Heymans]] in 1938 and [[Albert Claude]] together with [[Christian De Duve]] in 1974. [[Ilya Prigogine]] was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]] in 1977.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Nobel Prize in Chemistry 1977|url=http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/chemistry/laureates/1977/|publisher=Nobel Foundation|accessdate=December 9, 2010}}</ref> Two Belgian mathematicians have been awarded the [[Fields Medal]]: [[Pierre Deligne]] in 1978 and [[Jean Bourgain]] in 1994.<ref>{{MacTutor Biography|id=Deligne|title=Pierre Deligne}} (Retrieved: November 10, 2011)</ref><ref>{{MacTutor Biography|id=Bourgain|title=Jean Bourgain}} (Retrieved: November 10, 2011)</ref>

In February 2014, Belgium became the first country in the world to legalize [[euthanasia]] without any age limits.<ref>{{cite news|date=February 13, 2014|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-26181615|title=Belgium's parliament votes through child euthanasia|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=2014-02-13}}</ref>

==Culture==
===Fine arts===
[[File:eyck.hubert.lamb.750pix.jpg|thumb|''The [[Ghent Altarpiece]]: The Adoration of the Mystic Lamb'' (inside view), painted 1432 by [[Jan van Eyck|van Eyck]]]]

There have been many additions to painting and architecture. Several examples of major architectural places in Belgium belong to [[UNESCO]]'s [[World Heritage List]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Belgium|work=Properties inscribed on the World Heritage List|publisher=[[UNESCO]]|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/statesparties/be|accessdate=May 15, 2007}}</ref> In the 15th century the religious paintings of [[Jan van Eyck]] and [[Rogier van der Weyden]] were important. The 16th century had more styles such as [[Pieter Brueghel the Elder|Peter Breughel]]'s landscape paintings and [[Lambert Lombard]]'s showing of the antique.<ref>{{cite book|language=French|first=Jacques|last=Hendrick|title=La peinture au pays de Liège|year=1987|location=Liège|publisher=Editions du Perron|isbn=2-87114-026-X|page=24}}</ref> The style of [[Peter Paul Rubens]] and [[Anthony van Dyck]] was strong in the early 17th century in the Southern Netherlands.<ref>{{cite book|language=German|first=Herwig|last=Guratzsch|title=Die große Zeit der niederländische Malerei|year=1979
|publisher=Verlag Herder|location=Freiburg im Beisgau|page=7}}</ref>

During the 19th and 20th centuries many original [[romanticism|romantic]], [[expressionism|expressionist]] and [[surrealism|surrealist]] Belgian painters started. These include [[James Ensor]] and other artists in the [[Les XX]] group, [[Constant Permeke]], [[Paul Delvaux]] and [[René Magritte]]. The sculptor [[Panamarenko]] is still a remarkable figure in contemporary art.<ref>{{cite web|title=Belgian Artists: (biographies & artworks)|date=February 5, 2006|publisher=World Wide Arts Resources|url=http://wwar.com/masters/nationalities/belgian.html|accessdate=May 10, 2007|archive-date=May 15, 2016|archive-url=http://arquivo.pt/wayback/20160515200408/http://wwar.com/masters/nationalities/belgian.html|url-status=dead}}—List of Belgian painters, linking to their biographies and artworks</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Baudson, Michel|title=Panamarenko|publisher=Flammarion (Paris), quoted at presentation of the XXIII Bienal Internacional de São Paulo|year=1996|url=http://www1.uol.com.br/bienal/23bienal/universa/iueopa.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070207233008/http://www1.uol.com.br/bienal/23bienal/universa/iueopa.htm|archivedate=February 7, 2007|accessdate=May 10, 2007}}</ref> The artist [[Jan Fabre]] and the painter [[Luc Tuymans]] are other internationally known figures in contemporary art.

Belgian contributions to architecture were also in the 19th and 20th centuries. [[Victor Horta]] and [[Henry van de Velde]] were major starters of the [[Art Nouveau]] style.<ref>{{cite web|title=ib. (page2)|year=2007|publisher=Senses Art Nouveau Shop, Brussels|url=http://www.senses-artnouveau.com/brussels.php?page=2|accessdate=May 11, 2007|archive-date=March 4, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070304211919/http://www.senses-artnouveau.com/brussels.php?page=2|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Major Town Houses of the Architect Victor Horta (Brussels)|work=[[UNESCO]]'s [[World Heritage List]]|publisher=UNESCO
|url=http://whc.unesco.org/en/list/1005|accessdate=May 16, 2007}}</ref>

In the 19th and 20th centuries, there were major violinists, such as [[Henri Vieuxtemps]], [[Eugène Ysaÿe]] and [[Arthur Grumiaux]]. [[Adolphe Sax]] invented the [[saxophone]] in 1846. The composer [[César Franck]] was born in Liège in 1822. Newer music in Belgium is also famous. Jazz musician [[Toots Thielemans]] and singer [[Jacques Brel]] have made global fame. In rock/pop music, [[Telex (band)|Telex]], [[Front 242]], [[K's Choice]], [[Hooverphonic]], [[Zap Mama]], [[Soulwax]] and [[Deus (band)|dEUS]] are well known. In the heavy metal scene, bands like [[Machiavel]], [[Channel Zero (band)|Channel Zero]] and [[Enthroned]] have a worldwide fan-base.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Timeline—A brief history of Belgian Pop Music|date= March 2007|work=The Belgian Pop & Rock Archives|publisher=Flanders Music Centre, Brussels|url=http://houbi.com/belpop/timeline.htm
|accessdate=June 7, 2007}}</ref>

Belgium has several well-known authors, including the poet [[Emile Verhaeren]] and novelists [[Hendrik Conscience]], [[Georges Simenon]], [[Suzanne Lilar]] and [[Amélie Nothomb]]. The poet and playwright [[Maurice Maeterlinck]] won the [[Nobel Prize in literature]] in 1911. ''[[The Adventures of Tintin]]'' by [[Hergé]] is the best known of [[Franco-Belgian comics]]. Many other major authors, including [[Peyo]], [[André Franquin]], [[Edgar P. Jacobs]] and [[Willy Vandersteen]] brought the Belgian cartoon strip industry a worldwide fame.<ref>{{cite book|title=Comics in French: the European bande dessinée in context|author=Laurence Grove|publisher=Berghahn Books|year=2010|isbn=978-1-84545-588-0}}</ref>

Belgian cinema has brought a number of mainly Flemish novels to life on-screen. Belgian directors include [[André Delvaux]], [[Stijn Coninx]], [[Luc Dardenne|Luc]] and [[Jean-Pierre Dardenne]]. Well-known actors include [[Jan Decleir]] and [[Marie Gillain]]. Successful films include ''[[Man Bites Dog (film)|Man Bites Dog]]'' and ''[[The Alzheimer Affair]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=History of Cinema in Belgium|work=Film Birth|year=2007|url=http://www.filmbirth.com/belgium.html|accessdate=June 26, 2011|archive-date=September 14, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914135756/http://www.filmbirth.com/belgium.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>

===Cuisine===
[[File:Brussels waffle.jpg|right|thumb|upright|[[Brussels waffle]]s, commonly known as [[Belgian waffle]]s outside of Belgium]]
Belgium is famous for beer, chocolate, [[Belgian waffle|waffles]] and [[french fries]]. French fries were first made in Belgium. The national dishes are "steak and fries with salad", and "[[moules-frites|mussels with fries]]".<ref>{{cite web|title=Steak-frites|publisher=Epicurious|url=http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/recipe_views/views/40035|accessdate=August 12, 2007|archive-date=August 8, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070808152457/http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/recipe_views/views/40035|url-status=dead}}</ref>
Other local fast food dishes include a [[Mitraillette]]. Brands of Belgian chocolate and [[pralines]], like [[Côte d'Or (brand)|Côte d'Or]], [[Guylian]], [[Chocolatier Neuhaus|Neuhaus]], [[Leonidas (chocolate maker)|Leonidas]], Corné and Galler are famous.<ref>{{cite book | title=Belgium and Luxembourg | author=Mark Elliott, Geert Cole | publisher=Lonely Planet | year=2000 | page=53}}</ref> Belgium makes over 1100 varieties of beer.<ref name="BierbijbelNieuwsblad">{{cite news|url=http://www.nieuwsblad.be/article/detail.aspx?articleid=G2I3H7IVR|title=Nieuwe bierbijbel bundelt alle 1.132 Belgische bieren|first=Chris|last=Snick|date=October 18, 2011|language=Dutch|newspaper=Het Nieuwsblad|access-date=June 24, 2012|archive-date=June 5, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120605055509/http://www.nieuwsblad.be/article/detail.aspx?articleid=G2I3H7IVR|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name="BierbijbelKW">{{cite news|date=October 18, 2011|title=Nieuwe bierbijbel met 1.132 Belgische bieren voorgesteld in Brugge|language=Dutch|newspaper=Krant van West-Vlaanderen|url=https://kw.be/nieuws/nieuwe-bierbijbel-met-1-132-belgische-bieren-voorgesteld-in-brugge/|access-date=June 24, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120531221549/http://kw.knack.be/west-vlaanderen/nieuws/algemeen/nieuwe-bierbijbel-met-1-132-belgische-bieren-voorgesteld-in-brugge/article-1195119387827.htm|archive-date=May 31, 2012}}</ref> The [[Trappist beer]] of the [[Westvleteren Brewery|Abbey of Westvleteren]] has repeatedly been rated the world's best beer.<ref>{{cite news|last=Ames|first=Paul|title=Buying the World's Best Beer|url=http://www.globalpost.com/dispatch/benelux/090828/st-sixtus-westvleteren-beer|accessdate=November 19, 2010|newspaper=Global Post|date=August 30, 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last=Guthrie|first=Tyler|title=Day trip to the best beer in the world|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-08-11/travel/sc-trav-0810-strip-belgian-bike-trip-20100810_1_westvleteren-beer-day-trip|accessdate=November 19, 2010|newspaper=Chicago Tribune|date=August 11, 2010|archive-date=December 4, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204040743/http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2010-08-11/travel/sc-trav-0810-strip-belgian-bike-trip-20100810_1_westvleteren-beer-day-trip|url-status=dead}}</ref> The biggest brewer in the world by volume is [[Anheuser-Busch InBev]], based in [[Leuven]].<ref>{{cite press release|title=InBev dividend 2006: 0.72 euro per share—infobox: About InBev|quote=InBev is a publicly traded company ([[Euronext]]: INB) based in [[Leuven]], Belgium. The company's origins date back to 1366, and today it is the leading global brewer by volume.|date=24 April 200|publisher=InBev
|url=http://www.inbev.com/press_releases/20070424.1.e.cfm|accessdate=May 31, 2007}}</ref>

===Sports===
[[File:Kim Clijsters 2006.jpg|thumb|left|Kim Clijsters was [[WTA Awards|WTA Player of the Year]] in 2005 and 2010]]

Since the 1970s, sports clubs are organised separately by each language community.<ref>{{cite book|title=Organised sport in transition: development, structures and trends of sports clubs in Belgium|author1=Marijke Task|author2=Roland Renson|author3=Bart van Reusel|work=Sport clubs in various European countries|editor=Klaus Heinemann|publisher=Schattauer Verlag|year=1999|isbn=3-7945-2038-6|pages=183–229}}</ref> Association football is one of the most popular sports in both parts of Belgium, together with cycling, tennis, swimming and judo.<ref>{{cite book|title=Belgium|url=https://archive.org/details/belgium00wing|author=George Wingfield|publisher=Infobase Publishing|editor=Charles F. Gritzner|year=2008|isbn=978-0-7910-9670-3|pages=[https://archive.org/details/belgium00wing/page/94 94]–95}}</ref> With five victories in the [[Tour de France]] and many other cycling records, Belgian [[Eddy Merckx]] is said to be one of the greatest cyclists of all time.<ref>{{cite news|title=Great, but there are greater|author=Majendie, Matt|publisher=BBC Sport|date=April 18, 2005|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/cycling/3925265.stm|accessdate=September 20, 2007}}</ref> [[Jean-Marie Pfaff]], a former Belgian goalkeeper, is said to be one of the greatest in the history of football (soccer).<ref>"[http://www.goalkeepersaredifferent.com/keeper/goalkeeping_greats.htm Goalkeeping Greats]" Goalkeepersaredifferent.com. Retrieved on {{Nowrap|June 29}} 2008</ref> Belgium and The Netherlands hosted the [[UEFA European Football Championship]] in [[UEFA Euro 2000|2000]]. Belgium hosted the [[UEFA Euro 1972|1972 European Football Championships]].

[[Kim Clijsters]] and [[Justine Henin]] both were [[WTA Awards|Player of the Year]] in the [[Women's Tennis Association]]. The [[Spa-Francorchamps]] motor-racing circuit hosts the [[Formula One World Championship]] [[Belgian Grand Prix]]. The Belgian driver, [[Jacky Ickx]], won eight Grands Prix and six [[24 Hours of Le Mans]]. Belgium also has a strong reputation in [[motocross]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Motocross History: From Local Scrambling to World Championship MX to Freestyle|url=https://archive.org/details/motocrosshistory0000wood|author=Bob Woods|publisher=Crabtree Publishing Company| year=2008| isbn=978-0-7787-3987-6| page=[https://archive.org/details/motocrosshistory0000wood/page/19 19]}}</ref> Sporting events held each year in Belgium include the [[Memorial Van Damme]] athletics competition, the [[Belgian Grand Prix]] Formula One, and a number of [[classic cycle races]] such as the [[Tour of Flanders]] and [[Liège–Bastogne–Liège]]. The [[1920 Summer Olympics]] were held in Antwerp.
